    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A type of white, gray, or greenish serpentine that is characterized as being hard with a silky, fibrous structure. Chrysotile found in Cyprus and Afghanistan was used for beads, amulets, seals, and inlays; it was often misnamed as jade. It was the most common source of asbestos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
